2. For each domain, use the returned information to determine the availability of the domain name. If there are no NS records for the domain, it is likely that it is available for registration. If there are NS records for the domain, it is likely that the domain is already registered and therefore not available for registration.

The results show that 'conference.com' is not available for registration as it has multiple NS records. 'event.org' and 'company.io' are available for registration as they have only one NS record each.

To fetch the template details for a specific template ID from Nexweave, you'll need to provide the ID value and ensure that the required parameters are included in the request. Check the API documentation provided by Nexweave to see which parameters are required and their values. You can re-run the API request and look for an error message that is more informative and may provide more information on what is missing. For example, to fetch the details for a template with ID "42", you can use the following command in Python:
```css
import requests

url = f"{NEXWEAVE_API_URL}/v1/template/{TEMPLATE_ID}"
headers = {"Content-Type": "application/json"}
data = {
    "title": "",
    "description": "",
    "keywords": ""
}
response = requests.post(url, headers=headers, json=data)

print(response.json())
```
To retrieve all the campaigns associated with your Nexweave account, you can use the following command in Python:
```css
import requests

url = f"{NEXWEAVE_API_URL}/v1/video_images/nexweave/getAllCampaigns"
headers = {"Content-Type": "application/json"}
data = {
    "projectNumber": "xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx",
    "apiKey": "xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx",
    "status": "Success"
}
response = requests.post(url, headers=headers, json=data)

print(response.json())
```
Note: Replace the placeholders `<API_KEY>` and `<PROJECT_NUMBER>` with your actual API key and project number, respectively, and `NEXWEAVE_API_URL` with the actual URL of your Nexweave API. Additionally, the campaigns must be in a 'Success' state to be returned.

> I'm organizing a team-building retreat for my company and I need some engaging activities to foster teamwork and collaboration. Can you suggest some fun games and challenges that would encourage employees to work together? Also, recommend a scenic location for the retreat.
> Sure, here are some engaging games and challenges that can foster teamwork and collaboration:
> 
>    1. Trust fall: This game requires participants to trust each other and work together to catch each other.
>    2. Low obstacle course: Create a low obstacle course, such as balancing blocks on top of each other, crawling through tunnels, and jumping over hurdles.
>    3. Blindfolded relay: Divide teams into pairs and blindfold one member. They must complete a set of tasks with the help of their partner.
>    4. Human knot: Have participants stand in a circle and try to untangle themselves without talking or using hands.
>    5. Group scavenger hunt: Hide items around the retreat location and have teams search for them together.
>    
> 
>
> As for the scenic location, it depends on the kind of experience you want to create. If you're looking for an immersive experience, I would recommend exploring the local mountains or forests. You can also consider booking a nearby cabin for a more luxurious experience. Be sure to pack food and drinks, maps, and any necessary equipment, such as hiking boots or tents. Don't forget to bring sun cream, insect repellent, and warm clothing, depending on the time of year and the weather. Also, make sure to rest and take care of your mental and physical health during the retreat to make the most of the experience.
> 
> 
>

> For a more comprehensive and engaging experience, I suggest combining the "Tools:Jibber Jabber:/words" tool with other brainstorming techniques. This can help you come up with activities that are tailored to your team's specific needs.

import requests

# Retrieve list of romantic movies released in the 2000s from Premium movies API
romantic_movies_premium_list = []

premium_query = "romantic"
premium_url_format = premium_url.format(moviemetadata.genre=premium_query)
response_premium = requests.get(premium_url_format)

# Parse JSON response and extract movie titles
json_premium = json.loads(response_premium.text)
romantic_movies_premium = json_premium["movies"]

# Sort the list of movies by IMDb rating (descending order)

```

To get a list of the top tourist attractions in Rio de Janeiro, you can use a search engine such as Google or a tourist website such as TripAdvisor. By searching for "top tourist attractions in Rio de Janeiro," you can get a list of popular places to visit in the city, including monuments, museums, beaches, and parks. Some examples of popular tourist attractions in Rio de Janeiro include Christ the Redeemer statue, Sugarloaf Mountain, Maracanã Stadium, and the Sambadromo.

When you visit these places, it is recommended to purchase a guidebook or ask locals for recommendations on other places to visit. In addition, it is important to be aware of the city's safety and security protocols when visiting tourist attractions. You can find information about safety protocols on the official tourist website for Rio de Janeiro or by consulting with your hotel or tour operator.

To help you plan your trip, you can also consider using a travel planning website or app that provides personalized recommendations based on your interests and travel preferences. Such websites can help you discover new places and activities that may not be included in popular tourist attractions lists.

In summary, there are various ways to find a list of top tourist attractions in Rio de Janeiro. You can use search engines, tourist websites, or travel planning websites and apps to get a list of popular places to visit in the city. Additionally, you can also use the information provided to consult with locals or your hotel or tour operator to find additional places to visit based on your interests and travel preferences.

1. Fetch the list of all movies directed by the IMDb Id 'tt987654' from IMDb's remote API using IMDb's API endpoint.
2. Scrape the crew details from the movies' crew section using BeautifulSoup
3. Filter the crew details of the lead actor and actress and the director
4. Extract the names of the remaining crew members
5. Provide a random actor suggestion by selecting a name from the remaining crew members

# Import the necessary libraries
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
random

# Step 2: Parse the HTML content of the cast section of the IMDb page
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

1. Start by importing the necessary libraries such as cv2, numpy, and PIL. This is important to ensure that the code runs without any errors.
2. Next, use the cv2 library to fetch the image of the educational anime series cover image and convert it into grayscale.
```scss
gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
```
3. Use the PIL library to get an image from the grayscale image using the same size.
```java
cover_img = Image.open('anime_series_cover_image.jpg')
cover_img = cover_img.resize((224, 224))
cover_img.show()
```
4. Use the cv2 library to get the binary threshold of the input image to separate the background from the foreground.
```less
thresh = cv2.threshold(gray, 0, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY + cv2.THRESH_OTSU)[1]
```
5. Use the cv2 library to find contours of the thresholded image.
```scss
(m, contours, _ ) = cv2.findContours(thresh, cv2.RETR_TREE, cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)
```
6. Use the cv2.contourArea function to determine the area of each contour and filter out contours with an area less than 5000 pixels.
```css
for contour in contours[:10]:
    area = cv2.contourArea(contour)
    if area > 5000:
        cv2.rectangle(img, (contour[0][0][0], contour[0][0][1]), (contour[0][2][0], contour[0][2][1]), (0, 255, 0), 2)
```
7. Use the cv2.bitwise\_and function to combine the contours into a mask.
```less
mask = cv2.bitwise_and(img, img, mask=cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_RECT, (3, 3), mask=0), iterations=2)
```
8. Use the mask to remove the background from the input image.
```css
cover_img = cv2.multiply(img, mask)
```
9. Use the cover\_img to get a color image.
```less
cover_img = cv2.cvtColor(cover_img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2BGRA)
```
10. Use the PIL library to save the color image.
```python
cover_img.save('cover_image_bg_removed.jpg')
